The paper deals with the analysis of distributed algorithms in dynamic networks, which involves the study of network dynamics and their impact on algorithm execution. This topic falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). Additionally, the paper proposes a framework for expressing fine-grained properties on network dynamics and examining their impact on algorithm execution, which involves the use of evolving graphs and local computations. This framework involves the study of graph theory and algorithms, which falls under the category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI). The paper also discusses the potential for automated analysis and decision support in dynamic networks, which involves the study of network intelligence and decision-making, falling under the category of Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) and Systems and Control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper proposes a formal hierarchy of dynamic networks based on their topological requirements, which involves the study of machine learning and data analysis, falling under the category of Machine Learning (cs.LG).
